      <p><p>"We should also be talking about those contexts in which saying “yes” might actually mean “no”: contexts that might not amount to legal rape, but in which an abuse of power has nonetheless taken place that might be equivalent to it. No-one really seems to have mentioned this, but it’s important. 

You might be interested in this post which outlines some of the ways that patriarchy pressurises women to consent to sexual activity against their actual wishes.  Including through the male gaze which functions to make women see themselves as sexual objects; the legal system which puts them in a permanent legal state of consent, and rape culture which puts women in a double bind of being assumed as accessible to sexual activity simultaneously condemning them if they accept.

<a href="http://www.2ndcouncilhouse.co.uk/blog/2012/02/04/rape-eyes-laws-codes/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.2ndcouncilhouse.co.uk/blog/2012/02/04/rape-eyes-laws-codes/</a>

