    <div class="fyre-comment">
      <p><p>Assuming that a consent defence is lodged, the presumption of innocence over guilt suggests that the woman consented. It is for the prosecution to prove that she did not.  In most cases, x does not deny that penetration took place, only that it was consensual penetration.

x being found innocent implies that y consented, and consequently that y was not raped.

See more here

<a href="http://www.2ndcouncilhouse.co.uk/blog/2011/08/04/65/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.2ndcouncilhouse.co.uk/blog/2011/08/04/65/</a></p></p>
    </div>
    
